---
description: Enforces strict file and directory naming conventions across the project.
globs: '**/*'
alwaysApply: true
---

<rule>
  <context>
    This rule defines the global naming conventions for files and directories across the project.
    Consistent naming is critical for:
    - predictable routing and view resolution,
    - avoiding subtle bugs on case-sensitive operating systems (Linux/macOS),
    - keeping large teams aligned on where code lives and how to extend it safely.
  </context>

  <constraints>
    <section name="views-and-routes">
      <rule>
        Directories under <file>src/views</file> MUST use <code>kebab-case</code> names that describe the route or feature domain
        (for example <code>user-management</code>, <code>system-configuration</code>, <code>stats-grid</code>).
      </rule>
      <rule>
        For route views, each leaf view directory under <file>src/views</file> MUST contain either:
        - a single <code>index.vue</code> file, or
        - one or more <code>kebab-case.vue</code> files (for example <code>user-detail.vue</code>, <code>order-list.vue</code>).
      </rule>
      <rule>
        Do NOT use <code>PascalCase</code> or <code>camelCase</code> directory names under <file>src/views</file>.
        Routing-facing view directories are always <code>kebab-case</code> to keep URLs, file paths, and mental models aligned.
      </rule>
      <rule>
        Supporting TypeScript files colocated with views (for example <code>page.state.ts</code>, <code>useChartOptions.ts</code>, or config files)
        MUST follow the same directory naming convention and live under the corresponding <code>kebab-case</code> view folder.
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="components">
      <rule>
        Directories directly under <file>src/components</file> MUST use <code>PascalCase</code> names that match the conceptual component
        (for example <code>DataTable</code>, <code>SchemaForm</code>, <code>EmptyState</code>, <code>PrimeDialog</code>, <code>UseEcharts</code>).
      </rule>
      <rule>
        Vue single-file components inside <file>src/components</file> MUST use <code>PascalCase</code> filenames that match the component name
        (for example <code>DataTable.vue</code>, <code>DataTableV2.vue</code>, <code>AnimateWrapper.vue</code>, <code>EmptyState.vue</code>).
        Kebab-case component filenames inside <file>src/components</file> are not allowed.
      </rule>
      <rule>
        Internal utility subdirectories inside a component directory (for example <code>components</code>, <code>hooks</code>, <code>utils</code>, <code>composables</code>, <code>wrappers</code>)
        MUST use all-lowercase names.
        This keeps the distinction clear: <code>PascalCase</code> = exported component, lowercase = internal implementation detail.
      </rule>
      <rule>
        TypeScript and TSX files inside <file>src/components</file> that implement render helpers, presets, or supporting logic
        MUST follow camelCase filenames that describe their responsibility (for example <code>bodyCellRenderer.tsx</code>, <code>valueHelpers.ts</code>, <code>buildComponentProps.ts</code>),
        while keeping exported Vue components in <code>PascalCase.vue</code> files.
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="composables">
      <rule>
        All composable hooks under <file>src/hooks</file> MUST be implemented in files whose names start with <code>use</code> and follow <code>camelCase</code>
        (for example <code>useAdminTabs.ts</code>, <code>useMenuRenderer.tsx</code>, <code>useSchemaForm.ts</code>, <code>useDateUtils.ts</code>).
      </rule>
      <rule>
        Directory names under <file>src/hooks</file> (for example <code>layout</code>, <code>modules</code>) MUST be all lowercase and describe the grouping domain, not the specific hook.
      </rule>
      <rule>
        Each hook file SHOULD export a primary composable whose name exactly matches the filename (without extension),
        keeping <code>useXxx</code> as the single source of truth for that behavior.
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="infra-modules">
      <rule>
        Files and directories under <file>src/utils</file>, <file>src/api</file>, and <file>src/stores</file> MUST use <code>camelCase</code> naming.
        Examples: <code>chartUtils.ts</code>, <code>deviceSync.ts</code>, <code>userApi.ts</code>, <code>authStore.ts</code>, <code>themeEngine.ts</code>.
      </rule>
      <rule>
        Domain-level grouping directories in these areas MUST also use <code>camelCase</code>
        (for example <code>safeStorage</code>, <code>chartTheme</code>, <code>userManagement</code>),
        avoiding mixed <code>kebab-case</code> / <code>PascalCase</code> in the same tree.
      </rule>
      <rule>
        In <file>src/api</file>, the existing module/feature structure (<code>src/api/&lt;module&gt;/&lt;feature&gt;.ts</code>) remains required.
        This naming rule only clarifies that both <code>&lt;module&gt;</code> and <code>&lt;feature&gt;</code> segments MUST be <code>camelCase</code>.
      </rule>
      <rule>
        In <file>src/stores</file>, Pinia store files MUST use <code>camelCase</code> filenames suffixed with <code>Store</code> when they expose a store
        (for example <code>themeStore.ts</code>, <code>userStore.ts</code>, <code>layoutStore.ts</code>).
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="types-and-interfaces">
      <rule>
        TypeScript identifiers MUST follow the ESLint <code>@typescript-eslint/naming-convention</code> configuration:
        interfaces, type aliases, enums, enum members, and classes use <code>PascalCase</code>;
        variables, functions, parameters, and methods use <code>camelCase</code>;
        UPPER_CASE is reserved for constants where explicitly allowed.
      </rule>
      <rule>
        Type definition files that only contain shared types SHOULD be named <code>types.ts</code> when colocated with a feature,
        or <code>&lt;Feature&gt;Types.ts</code> when stored in a central types folder (for example <code>UserTypes.ts</code>, <code>TableTypes.ts</code>).
      </rule>
      <rule>
        Under <file>src/types</file> (and its subdirectories), filenames SHOULD use <code>PascalCase</code> plus a <code>Types</code> suffix for domain-specific type collections
        (for example <code>ThemeTypes.ts</code>, <code>RouterTypes.ts</code>), and may use <code>types.d.ts</code> where ambient declarations are required.
      </rule>
    </section>
  </constraints>

  <forbidden>
    <item>
      NEVER use <code>PascalCase</code> directory names under <file>src/views</file>.
      Examples of forbidden directories: <code>UserManagement/</code>, <code>StatsGrid/</code>, <code>RouterMetaExample/</code>.
      These MUST be renamed to their <code>kebab-case</code> equivalents (for example <code>user-management/</code>, <code>stats-grid/</code>).
    </item>
    <item>
      NEVER use <code>kebab-case</code> filenames for Vue components under <file>src/components</file>.
      Component SFCs in this directory MUST be <code>PascalCase.vue</code> (for example <code>DataTable.vue</code>, not <code>data-table.vue</code>).
    </item>
    <item>
      NEVER mix different casing styles within the same functional domain.
      For example, in <file>src/utils/theme</file> do not combine <code>primevueThemeEngine.ts</code>, <code>chartUtils.ts</code>, and <code>colorAdapter.ts</code> forever;
      over time the folder MUST converge on a single casing style (<code>camelCase</code> for files and directories in this rule).
    </item>
  </forbidden>

  <communication>
    Output Requirement: Always explain file renaming, structural changes, and naming violations to the user in fluent Chinese.
    Keep file paths and exact code identifiers in English so they can be copied directly into the editor, git logs, and CLI commands.
  </communication>

  <examples>
    <example>
      Good (aligned with this rule):
      <code-block language="text">
src/
  views/
    user-management/
      index.vue
      page.state.ts
    system-configuration/
      index.vue

  components/
    DataTable/
      DataTable.vue
      DataTableV2.vue
      utils/
        columnUtils.ts

  hooks/
    layout/
      useAdminTabs.ts
      useAdminBreadcrumbs.ts

  utils/
    chartUtils.ts
    deviceSync.ts

  api/
    user/
      userApi.ts

  stores/
    auth/
      authStore.ts
      </code-block>
    </example>

    <example>
      Bad (violates this rule):
      <code-block language="text">
src/
  views/
    UserManagement/
      UserManagement.vue
    StatsGrid/
      StatsGrid.vue

  components/
    data-table/
      data-table.vue

  hooks/
    layout/
      adminTabs.ts

  utils/
    primevueThemeEngine.ts
    chart_utils.ts
      </code-block>
    </example>
  </examples>
</rule>

